<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,775,1376]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
The female terminalia of the 
<typeStatus box="[523,621,775,800]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rafael, J. A." box="[635,843,775,800]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" pagination="733 - 739" refId="ref18805" refString="Rafael, J. A. (1995) Revisao das especies Neotropicais de Empididae (Diptera) descritas por Mario Bezzi. II. Tachydromiinae. Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 39, 733 - 739." type="journal article" year="1995">Rafael 1995, fig. 1</bibRefCitation>
) shows that the species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[1252,1396,775,800]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albivertex" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1252,1396,775,800]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. albivertex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[213,326,811,836]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aliceae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[213,326,811,836]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. aliceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[333,422,811,836]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[333,422,811,836]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[482,618,811,836]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goliathus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[482,618,811,836]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. goliathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[625,714,811,836]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[625,714,811,836]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
due to the presence of a mediodorsal depression on tergite 8, but none of these species have the anterior margin of tergite 8 so deeply concave as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1103,1228,848,871]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armipes">
<emphasis box="[1103,1228,848,871]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. armipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Also, the slender shape of sternite 
<quantity box="[345,389,883,908]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[397,522,884,907]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armipes">
<emphasis box="[397,522,884,907]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. armipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to that in 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[754,900,883,908]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albivertex" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[754,900,883,908]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. albivertex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[908,998,883,908]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[908,998,883,908]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but in the former species sternite 8 is wider apically, while in the latter species sternite 8 is narrower towards the apex. Moreover, the sternite is medially divided in the apical 1/2 and the lateroapical portion of sternite 
<quantity box="[861,904,955,980]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[910,1024,955,980]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aliceae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[910,1024,955,980]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. aliceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1031,1120,955,980]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1031,1120,955,980]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and in 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[1203,1340,955,980]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goliathus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1203,1340,955,980]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. goliathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1347,1436,955,980]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1347,1436,955,980]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is bent upwards. Although the female terminalia have the cerci+epiproct (= tergite 10) and part of the hypoproct (sternite 10) broken in Rafael’s figure, Bezzi’s original description states the cerci are vertical (
<bibRefCitation author="Bezzi, M." box="[1232,1424,1027,1052]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" pagination="297 - 406" refId="ref16851" refString="Bezzi, M. (1909) Beitrage zur Kenntniss der sudamerikanischen Dipterenfauna auf Grund der Sammelergebnisse einer Reise in Chile, Peru und Bolivia, ausgefuhrt in den Jahren 1902 - 1904 von W. Schnuse. Fam. Empididae. Nova Acta Academiae Caesareae Leopoldino-Carolinae Germanicae Naturae Curiosorum, 91 (3), 297 - 406." type="journal article" year="1909">Bezzi 1909: 400</bibRefCitation>
), which can also be seen in 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[443,588,1063,1088]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albivertex" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[443,588,1063,1088]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. albivertex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[595,684,1063,1088]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[595,684,1063,1088]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha, 2019" authorityName="Freitas-Silva &amp; Ale-Rocha" authorityYear="2019" box="[739,852,1063,1088]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aliceae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[739,852,1063,1088]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C. aliceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[859,948,1063,1088]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[859,942,1063,1088]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,775,1376]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
The type locality of Tacna is indicated in all previous literature of the species as belonging to 
<collectingCountry box="[1242,1306,1099,1124]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Chile</collectingCountry>
. In fact, the Province of Tacna was legally part of 
<collectingCountry box="[601,661,1135,1160]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Chile</collectingCountry>
as a result of a peace agreement between 
<collectingCountry box="[1164,1224,1135,1160]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Chile</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1286,1337,1136,1159]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Peru</collectingCountry>
in 1883 (Treaty of Ancón) sealing the end of the Pacific War (
<date box="[754,886,1172,1196]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" value="1879" valueMax="1883">1879–1883</date>
). Later, in 1929, 
<collectingRegion box="[1076,1142,1172,1195]" country="Peru" name="Tacna" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Tacna</collectingRegion>
was reassigned to 
<collectingCountry box="[1354,1405,1172,1195]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Peru</collectingCountry>
as result of the Treaty of 
<collectingRegion box="[421,483,1207,1232]" country="Peru" name="Lima" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Lima</collectingRegion>
, but the record of the occurrence of the species in 
<collectingCountry box="[1090,1150,1207,1232]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Chile</collectingCountry>
has persisted. Thus, the occurrence here is updated taking into account these historical facts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,775,1376]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">
The 
<typeStatus box="[251,349,1279,1304]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">holotype</typeStatus>
remained for years as the single known specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[962,1086,1280,1303]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Crossopalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armipes">
<emphasis box="[962,981,1280,1303]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[996,1086,1280,1303]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">armipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, before 
<bibRefCitation author="Raffone, G." box="[1182,1355,1279,1304]" pageId="9" pageNumber="120" pagination="97 - 101" refId="ref18843" refString="Raffone, G. (2012) New or interesting records of Diptera Empididae and Hybotidae from Bolivia with description of Platypalpus pseudomollitus n. sp. (Insecta, Diptera, Brachycera). Bollettino del Museo di Storia Naturale di Fenezia, 63, 97 - 101." type="journal article" year="2012">Raffone (2012)</bibRefCitation>
record the species from 
<collectingCountry box="[347,429,1315,1340]" name="Bolivia" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[446,572,1316,1340]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
Dept.) (
<figureCitation box="[670,756,1315,1340]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[176,1413,265,1708]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[176,1413,265,1708]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 36. Crossopalpus Bigot. Geographical records of the South American species. Biogeographical regionalization follows Morrone (2014), implemented with the shapefiles of Löwenberg-Neto (2014)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2626765/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="120">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
). Perhaps, the validity of this record needs to be revaluated (this issue is examined further under the subheading Distribution in the Discussion section below).
</paragraph>
